In regard to the current density of the probability (of finding the electron along the tube) per Fermi velocity, Fig. 4c portrays the positive current at the right side and negative current at the left side. At the time 0.1 T, the current takes place between about -9.61nm\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$-9.61 \;  \text{nm}$$\end{document} and 9.92 nm with the right side’s maximum 5.93 and the left side’s maximum − 6.08, whereas at time 0.2 T, the current emerges from -13.84\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
